uture\u002Farticle\u002F20160211-the-secret-anti-languages-youre-not-supposed-to-know":{"urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:article:future\u002Farticle\u002F20160211-the-secret-anti-languages-youre-not-supposed-to-know","_id":"5e982096272a584021aaf193","ambientVideo":"","articleType":"story","assetVideo":null,"author":[],"bodyIntro":"From London to Timbuktu, there is a teeming underworld of rebellious “anti-societies” who speak a mercurial, ever-changing code. Their words are, quite literally, gobbledygook designed to confuse authority.","businessUnit":"worldwide","cards":[{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003ECould you \u003Cem\u003Eerectify a luxurimole flackoblots\u003C\u002Fem\u003E? Have you hidden your \u003Cem\u003Echocolate cake \u003C\u002Fem\u003Efrom \u003Cem\u003EPenelope\u003C\u002Fem\u003E? Or maybe you&rsquo;re just going to \u003Cem\u003Evada the\u003C\u002Fem\u003E \u003Cem\u003Ebona omi\u003C\u002Fem\u003E?\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf you understand any of these sentences, you speak an English &ldquo;anti-language&rdquo;. Since at least Tudor times, secret argots have been used in the underworld of prisoners, escaped slaves and criminal gangs as a way of confusing and befuddling the authorities.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThieves&rsquo; Cant, Polari, and Gobbledygook (yes, it&rsquo;s a real form of slang) are just a few of the examples from the past &ndash; but anti-languages are mercurial beasts that are forever evolving into new and more vibrant forms.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA modern anti-language could very well be spoken on the street outside your house. Unless you yourself are a member of the &ldquo;anti-society&rdquo;, the strange terms would sound like nonsense. Yet those words may have nevertheless influenced your swear words, the comedy you enjoy and the music on your iPod &ndash; without you even realising the shady interactions that shaped them.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160211-the-secret-anti-languages-youre-not-supposed-to-know-0"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160211-the-secret-anti-languages-youre-not-supposed-to-know-1"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EOne of the first detailed records of an anti-language comes from a 16th Century magistrate called Thomas Harman. Standing at his front door, he offered food and money to passing beggars in return for nothing more than words. &ldquo;He would say 'either I throw you in prison or you give me your Cant,'&rdquo; explains Jonathon Green, whose latest book is \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fjonathongreen.co.uk\u002Fwork\u002F\"\u003ELanguage: 500 Years of the Vulgar Tongue\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160211-the-secret-anti-languages-youre-not-supposed-to-know-2"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Byng we to Rome vyle to nyp a bounge, so shall we have lower for the bowsing ken &ndash; Thieves&rsquo; Cant","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160211-the-secret-anti-languages-youre-not-supposed-to-know-3"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EAs Green points out, many slang words concern our basest preoccupations. &ldquo;Slang may not represent us at our best, or our most admirable, but it represents us as human beings with anger, fear, self-aggrandisement, and our obsession with sex and bodily parts.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EYet the Thieves&rsquo; Cant also includes some intricacies that are not found in the informal language you or I speak. They are perhaps best illustrated by a dialogue between two vagabonds, which Harman recorded in his book \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fia800501.us.archive.org\u002F2\u002Fitems\u002Facaveatorwarnin00harmgoog\u002Facaveatorwarnin00harmgoog.pdf\"\u003EA Caveat or Warning for Common Cursitors.\u003C\u002Fa\u003E &ldquo;Byng we to Rome vyle to nyp a bounge, so shall we have lower for the bowsing ken,&rdquo; one suggests. Harman translates the phrase as &ldquo;Let&rsquo;s go to London and cut a purse, so we shall have money for the alehouse&rdquo; &ndash; a meaning that would be almost completely indecipherable for people who were not in the know.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA &ldquo;prigger of prancers&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFour centuries later, Harman&rsquo;s glossary would help inspire British-born linguist Michael Halliday to \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fonlinelibrary.wiley.com\u002Fdoi\u002F10.1525\u002Faa.1976.78.3.02a00050\u002Fepdf\"\u003Edefine the term &ldquo;anti-language&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fa\u003E in the 1970s, to describe the words spoken on the fringes of society. Comparing Thieves&rsquo; Cant to more recent analyses of the slang spoken in Calcutta (now commonly spelt as Kolkata) and elaborate &ldquo;Grypserka&rdquo; found among the inmates of Polish prisons, he found striking similarities in the patois spoken by all three underground groups and the ways it shaped their interactions.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160211-the-secret-anti-languages-youre-not-supposed-to-know-4"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Elizabethan criminals used at least 20 terms to describe fellow thieves, including &ldquo;prigger of prancers&rdquo;, &ldquo;doxy&rdquo;, &ldquo;dell&rdquo;, &ldquo;counterfeit crank&rdquo;, &ldquo;jarkman&rdquo; and &ldquo;bawdy basket&rdquo;","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160211-the-secret-anti-languages-youre-not-supposed-to-know-5"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EAll borrow the grammar of the mother language but replace words (&ldquo;London&rdquo;, &ldquo;purse&rdquo;, &ldquo;money&rdquo;, &ldquo;alehouse&rdquo;) with another, elliptical term (&ldquo;Rome&rdquo;, &ldquo;bounge&rdquo;, &ldquo;lower&rdquo;, &ldquo;bowsing ken&rdquo;). Often, the anti-language may employ dozens of terms that have blossomed from a single concept &ndash; a feature known as &ldquo;over-lexicalisation&rdquo;. Halliday points to at least 20 terms that Elizabethan criminals used to describe fellow thieves, for instance: &ldquo;prigger of prancers&rdquo;, &ldquo;doxy&rdquo;, &ldquo;dell&rdquo;, &ldquo;counterfeit crank&rdquo;, &ldquo;jarkman&rdquo; and &ldquo;bawdy basket&rdquo;, to name just a handful.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESimilarly, the Kolkata underworld had 41 words for police and more than 20 for bomb. Each anti-society may have its own way of generating new terms; often the terms are playful metaphors (such as &ldquo;bawdy basket&rdquo;), but they can also be formed from existing words by swapping around or inserting syllables &ndash; &ldquo;face&rdquo; might become &ldquo;ecaf&rdquo;, for instance.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160211-the-secret-anti-languages-youre-not-supposed-to-know-6"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160211-the-secret-anti-languages-youre-not-supposed-to-know-7"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThis clever, playful use of metaphor would come to define anti-languages for Halliday. As you could see from the dialogue between the two Elizabethan ruffians, the strange, nonsensical words render a sentence almost impossible to comprehend for outsiders, and the more terms you have, the harder it is for an outsider to learn the code. It is the reason that selling words to the police can be heavily punished among underworld gangs.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160211-the-secret-anti-languages-youre-not-supposed-to-know-8"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Refusing to speak the lingo denigrated you to the lowest rung of the prison hierarchy","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160211-the-secret-anti-languages-youre-not-supposed-to-know-9"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EHalliday doubted that secrecy was the only motive for building an anti-language, though; he found that it also helps define a hierarchy within the &ldquo;anti-society&rdquo;. Among the Polish prisoners, refusing to speak the lingo could denigrate you to the lowest possible rung of the social ladder, the so-called &ldquo;suckers&rdquo;. Needless to say, these individuals had a rougher time than those who had bothered to immerse themselves in the vocabulary.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;The better you are, the higher the status between those users,&rdquo; explains Martin Montgomery, author of An Introduction to Language and Society.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160211-the-secret-anti-languages-youre-not-supposed-to-know-10"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"One of the most elaborate forms of anti-language can be found in a remote village 250 kilometres south of Timbuktu","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160211-the-secret-anti-languages-youre-not-supposed-to-know-11"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThe concept of an anti-language throws light on many of the vibrant slangs at the edges of society, from Cockney rhyming slang and Victorian &ldquo;Gobbledygook&rdquo; to the &ldquo;Mobspeak&rdquo; of the Mafia and &ldquo;\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fir.canterbury.ac.nz\u002Fbitstream\u002Fhandle\u002F10092\u002F4789\u002Flooser_thesis_vol1.pdf;jsessionid=ECEEC33B43FAFC8A4C0AC2B5B7865254?sequence=1\"\u003EBoobslang\u003C\u002Fa\u003E&rdquo; found uniquely in New Zealand prisons. The breadth and range of the terms can be astonishing; a \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fir.canterbury.ac.nz\u002Fhandle\u002F10092\u002F4789\"\u003Elexicography of Boobslang\u003C\u002Fa\u003E reaches more than 200 pages, with 3,000 entries covering many areas of life. To be &ldquo;under the thumb&rdquo; is to be in love, a &ldquo;double yoker&rdquo; is an idiot, a &ldquo;cue ball&rdquo; is a skinhead and a &ldquo;goodnight kiss&rdquo; is a knockout punch. Outside of prison, each type of crime will have its own specialised vocabulary. A 1980s survey of American confidence tricksters, for instance, found a variety of colourful names for their intended victims &ndash; they are \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fciteseerx.ist.psu.edu\u002Fviewdoc\u002Fdownload?doi=10.1.1.471.6464&amp;rep=rep1&amp;type=pdf#page=45\"\u003Ean &ldquo;apple&rdquo;, an &ldquo;egg&rdquo;, a &ldquo;fink&rdquo;, or, most innocuously sounding, &ldquo;Mr Bates&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160211-the-secret-anti-languages-youre-not-supposed-to-know-12"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160211-the-secret-anti-languages-youre-not-supposed-to-know-13"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EOne of the most elaborate forms of anti-language can be found in a remote canyon in Mali, 250 kilometres south of Timbuktu. Living in a remote village carved out of the edge of a massive cliff, the Bangande (literally translated as &ldquo;furtive ones&rdquo;) are reportedly descended from escaped slaves, which may have led them to evolve a clandestine vocabulary that they could use to fool passing traders. Sometimes, it involved reversing the meaning of words &ndash; a black tree was described as being white, for instance &ndash; a simple trick that would confound those who were not in the know.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs a sign of just how much they valued their privacy, the linguist Abbie Hantgan reports having lived with the locals for years before her friends finally \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.newscientist.com\u002Farticle\u002Fmg22229710-700-people-of-secrets-the-slave-sanctuary-anti-language\u002F\"\u003Erevealed the anti-language\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther anti-languages have thrived and then withered as their tabboos faded &ndash; but they nevertheless leave a lasting mark on our culture. Consider Polari. Incorporating elements of criminal cants, the gypsy Romani language, and Italian words, it was eventually adopted by the gay community of early 20th Century Britain, when homosexuality was still illegal. (Taking a &ldquo;vada&rdquo; at a &ldquo;bona omi&rdquo; for instance, means take a look at the good-looking man). Dropping an innocent term into a conversation would have been \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Flanguagecontact.humanities.manchester.ac.uk\u002FMcrLC\u002Fcasestudies\u002FHT\u002FHT_Polari.pdf\"\u003Ea way of identifying another gay man\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, without the risk of incriminating yourself among people who were not in the know.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160211-the-secret-anti-languages-youre-not-supposed-to-know-14"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160211-the-secret-anti-languages-youre-not-supposed-to-know-15"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Kenneth Williams&rsquo; graphic innuendo shows us the power of anti-languages to subvert &ndash; by using the establishment's \"Auntie\" to broadcast shocking scenes of gay culture","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160211-the-secret-anti-languages-youre-not-supposed-to-know-16"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThe wit and word play of Polari soon became central elements of &ldquo;camp&rdquo; humour, influencing family favourites such as the Carry On films. The most outrageous example was possibly Kenneth Williams&rsquo; popular BBC radio show Round the Horne, which used graphic innuendo to bring gay culture into even the most conservative of living rooms. Ostensibly talking about music, for instance, one character describes &ldquo;a miracle of dexterity at the cottage upright&rdquo;. The phrase may have sounded innocent enough for those who did not know that &ldquo;cottage&rdquo; means &ldquo;public toilet&rdquo; and &ldquo;upright&rdquo; refers to an erection.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis success is a startling illustration of the power of an anti-language to subvert &ndash; using the establishment's prudish \"\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.theguardian.com\u002Fnotesandqueries\u002Fquery\u002F0,5753,-23572,00.html\"\u003EAuntie\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\"&nbsp; to broadcast shocking scenes of gay culture, two years before the Sexual Offences Act decriminalised homosexuality. The show may have only got the green light thanks to the fact that the radio commissioners either didn&rsquo;t understand the connotations &ndash; or at least, didn&rsquo;t want to admit they understood them.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160211-the-secret-anti-languages-youre-not-supposed-to-know-17"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"David Bowie&rsquo;s last album was written as a combination of Polari and Nadsat, the fictional anti-language in Anthony Burgess&rsquo;s A Clockwork Orange","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160211-the-secret-anti-languages-youre-not-supposed-to-know-18"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EWith the growing gay rights movement, however, a secret anti-language was no longer necessary, or wanted, and Polari began to crumble. But it has left its mark in the words and phrases such as &ldquo;camp&rdquo;, &ldquo;palaver&rdquo;, &ldquo;butch&rdquo; and &ldquo;naff&rdquo; (which was used as a rude acronym denoting someone who is sexually unavailable.) And artists continue to use its playful terms as a source of inspiration; the song \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fen.wikipedia.org\u002Fwiki\u002FGirl_Loves_Me\"\u003EGirl Loves Me\u003C\u002Fa\u003E on David Bowie&rsquo;s latest album was written as a combination of Polari and Nadsat, the fictional anti-language in Anthony Burgess&rsquo;s A Clockwork Orange.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160211-the-secret-anti-languages-youre-not-supposed-to-know-19"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160211-the-secret-anti-languages-youre-not-supposed-to-know-20"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EMontgomery thinks we can see a similar process in the lyrics of hip-hop music. As with the other anti-languages, you can witness the blossoming of words for the illegal activities that might accompany gang culture. &ldquo;There are so many words for firearm, for different kinds of drug, for money,&rdquo; says Montgomery, who is based at the University of Macau. The police, for instance, are variously known as &ldquo;berry&rdquo;, &ldquo;elroys&rdquo;, and &ldquo;Penelope&rdquo;; crack cocaine can be known as &ldquo;German chocolate cake&rdquo;, &ldquo;hubba&rdquo; or &ldquo;a slab&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAgain, the imaginitive terms lend themselve to artistic use. &ldquo;There&rsquo;s quite often a playful element you elaborate new terms for old,&rdquo; Montgomery says. &ldquo;To use broccoli as a word for a drug &ndash; you take a word from the mainstream and convert it to new use and it has semi-humorous twist to it.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe thinks that the web will only encourage the creation of slang that share some of the qualities of anti-languages; you just need to look at the rich online vocabulary that has emerged to describe prostitution; those seeking the services of a sex worker are \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fjce.sagepub.com\u002Fcontent\u002F38\u002F5\u002F619.refs\"\u003E&ldquo;practicing the hobby&rdquo;, &ldquo;trolling&rdquo; or &ldquo;mongering&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fa\u003E Montgomery points out that new, metaphorical forms of speech will also proliferate in areas threatened by state censorship; already, you can see a dozen euphemisms flourishing in place of every term that is blocked from a search engine or social network. &nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf we can learn anything from this rich history of criminal cants, it is the enormous resilience of human expression in the face of oppression. When considering the poetry of English, we rarely think of the thieves, drug dealers and prostitutes who helped form it. Yet our language may be at its richest and most powerful when it is driven underground.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E--\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EDavid Robson is BBC Future&rsquo;s feature writer. He is \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftwitter.com\u002Fd_a_robson\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003E@d_a_robson\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E on twitter\u003C\u002Fem\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EJoin 500,000+ Future fans by liking us on \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002FBBCFuture\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003EFacebook\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E, or follow us on \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftwitter.com\u002Fbbc_future\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003ETwitter\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E, \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fplus.google.com\u002F107828172298602173375\u002Fposts\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003EGoogle+\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E, \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.linkedin.com\u002Fcompany\u002Fbbc-com\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003ELinkedIn\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E and \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Finstagram.com\u002Fbbcfuture_official\u002F\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003EInstagram\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EIf you liked this story,&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fpages.emails.bbc.com\u002Fsubscribe\u002F\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003Esign up for the weekly bbc.com features newsletter\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E, called &ldquo;If You Only Read 6 Things This Week&rdquo;. A handpicked selection of stories from BBC Future, Earth, Culture, Capital, Travel and Autos, delivered to your inbox every Friday\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160211-the-secret-anti-languages-youre-not-supposed-to-know-21"}],"collection":[],"disableAdverts":false,"displayDate":"2016-02-12T13:35:34Z","embeddedCustomHtml":"","embeddedInfographicUrl":"","embeddedType":"","geolocation":null,"headlineLong":"The secret “anti-languages” you’re not supposed to know","headlineShort":"The secret languages of the underworld","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageAltText":"","isSyndicated":true,"latitude":"","location":null,"longitude":"","mpsVideo":"","option":[],"partner":null,"primaryVertical":"future","promoAlignment":"centre","promoAltText":"","promoImage":null,"relatedStories":[],"relatedTag":null,"summaryLong":"From London to Timbuktu, there is a teeming underworld of rebellious “anti-societies” who speak a mercurial code. David Robson reports","summaryShort":"Subversive lingoes you're not supposed to know","tag":[],"creationDateTime":"2016-02-12T04:37:04.003257Z","entity":"article","guid":"83b44312-1310-4031-92dc-b8c943fa0b4b","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160211-the-secret-anti-languages-youre-not-supposed-to-know","modifiedDateTime":"2019-10-04T14:34:19.621893Z","project":"future","slug":"20160211-the-secret-anti-languages-youre-not-supposed-to-know","cacheLastUpdated":1587442999741},"future\u002Farticle\u002F20130328-who-owns-the-meaning-of-words":{"urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:article:future\u002Farticle\u002F20130328-who-owns-the-meaning-of-words","_id":"5e982090272a584021aad6c4","ambientVideo":"","articleType":"story","assetVideo":null,"author":[],"bodyIntro":"How do you say “something that cannot be found on the web using a search engine” in Swedish?","businessUnit":"worldwide","cards":[{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EUntil this week, you could have said ogooglebar, a term sanctioned by no less than the Language Council of Sweden, and roughly equivalent to the English speaker&rsquo;s mouthful &ldquo;ungooglable.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnfortunately for search-challenged Scandinavians, Google didn&rsquo;t like the idea of its name being part of a general term for online search, and suggested amending the definition to describe only searches performed via Google. The Language Council &ndash; which is dedicated to documenting the emergence of new words in Swedish &ndash; didn&rsquo;t think much of this, or fancy a lengthy legal process. So the word was removed from the official list of new Swedish terms.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhether absence from this list will make much difference to Swedish speaking habits remains to be seen, although it seems unlikely. As the Council put it in an \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.sprakradet.se\u002F15922\"\u003Eonline statement on 26th March\u003C\u002Fa\u003E &ndash; at least so far as I can tell, courtesy of none other than Google&rsquo;s translation service &ndash; &ldquo;Google has namely forgot one thing: language development do not care about brand protection. No individual can decide about the language.&rdquo; The grammar may be iffy, but the point is clear. Courtesy of the internet, the furore around ogooglebar is likely only to spread its usage.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere are larger concerns at stake here, however. I&rsquo;ve spent much of the last year writing \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Ftomchatfield.net\u002F\"\u003Ea book about language and technology\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, and the rise of &ldquo;ungooglable&rdquo; and its international equivalents marks one of the most characteristic linguistic evolutions of our age: binary vocabulary.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUnfollow, unfriend\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETo take just a handful of terms, consider what it means to &ldquo;like&rdquo; and to &ldquo;unlike&rdquo;, or to &ldquo;favourite&rdquo; and to &ldquo;unfavourite&rdquo;; how you can &ldquo;follow&rdquo; and &ldquo;unfollow&rdquo;, or &ldquo;friend&rdquo; and &ldquo;unfriend&rdquo;, other people; and how you constantly &ldquo;click&rdquo; or &ldquo;unclick&rdquo; onscreen boxes.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn each case, what&rsquo;s on offer is a near-miraculous promise of agency: the possibility of words and actions that are, unlike those taking place in the real world, entirely reversible. There&rsquo;s nothing that cannot be undone in an instant, then done again at will (the word &ldquo;undone&rdquo; itself has existed in English for around 700 years but, when Shakespeare and his predecessors used it, they usually implied death or destruction: a far cry from pressing &ldquo;Ctrl-Z&rdquo; on a keyboard).\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEven &ldquo;ungoogleable&rdquo; has a reassuring kind of certainty to it. On the one hand lies the ordered, searchable realm within which we conduct our daily digital business. On the other, there&rsquo;s the stuff we&rsquo;re best off not worrying about: a \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.co.uk\u002Fnews\u002Fmagazine-21956743\"\u003Emessy, unsearachable space\u003C\u002Fa\u003E spanning everything from cyber-dissidents to criminals, via paywalls and anonymous networks.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EExcept, of course, the boxes of online experience are never quite as tidy as they seem. &ldquo;Untag&rdquo; yourself from an embarrassing public image &ndash; or indeed from an image that doesn&rsquo;t actually show you at all &ndash; and both the deed and the undeed will remain recorded forever. Unfollow or unfriend someone you know and they will vanish from view &ndash; but they may well never forget or forgive. No matter how many times you click undo, the machine records and remembers.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EReversible words promise a kind of perpetual present, in which everything can always be exactly the way you want it (provided you only feel one of two ways). Yet data itself only accumulates. Whether you consider yourself to be ogooglebar or not, the digital book of your life is steadily being written within somebody&rsquo;s servers &ndash; and few of its words will ever be unwritten.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E&lsquo;Ugly gloop&rsquo;\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAll of which makes the ownership of words an important battleground. In Lewis Carroll&rsquo;s Alice Through The Looking Glass, Humpty Dumpty explains to Alice that &ldquo;When I use a word, it means just what I choose it to mean &ndash; neither more nor less.&rdquo; Carroll was using absurdity to make a simple point: language is something we build together, and I can no more choose the precise meaning of my words than I can decide which laws of physics apply to me. Google, however, seem determined to play Humpty Dumpty &ndash; and in the process to make a very particular kind of binary claim. Either you use &ldquo;Google&rdquo; their way, or you don&rsquo;t get to use it all.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECommercial imperatives may be at stake, not least around the vexed question of trademarks, but there&rsquo;s also an old-fashioned petulance to this insistence: as if official approval still governed the way we judge language. Given that most of us are likely simply to type a word into Google if we want to check its meaning, this puts the company in a curiously invidious position. Should it describe words as people are using them, or suggest in certain cases how things &ldquo;ought&rdquo; to be?\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAccurately reflecting the world has always been a sacrosanct principle for search. When it comes to language, though, every act of selection and interconnection itself adds another layer of meaning (just start typing into a search box to find out what auto-completed ideas are associated with your name). &nbsp;If you can&rsquo;t find something online, it&rsquo;s often because you lack the right words. And there&rsquo;s a deliciously circular logic to all this, whereby what&rsquo;s &ldquo;right&rdquo; means only what displays the best search results &ndash; just as what you yourself &ldquo;like&rdquo; is defined by the boxes you&rsquo;ve ticked.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn the end, then, the Swedish Language Council&rsquo;s statement of language&rsquo;s independence from influence may not be quite as convincing as it seems. While no individual can decide the future of language, does the same apply to the software through which so many millions of our words flow each day?\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;Ungooglable&rdquo; is an ugly gloop of a word (ogooglebar is much more mellifluous), but it&rsquo;s also a tribute to a certain species of contemporary power &ndash; and the ways in which some tools can shape not only how we communicate, but what we say, what we&rsquo;re not allowed to say, and what the world thinks we mean. Language online may seem a simple, binary business. But there&rsquo;s always more to be said at the margins of words.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EDo you agree with Tom? If you would like to comment on this story or anything else you have seen on Future, head over to our \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002FBBCFuture\"\u003EFacebook\u003C\u002Fa\u003E page or message us on \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftwitter.com\u002F#%21\u002FBBC_Future\"\u003ETwitter\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20130328-who-owns-the-meaning-of-words-0"}],"collection":[],"disableAdverts":false,"displayDate":"2014-11-18T09:14:40Z","embeddedCustomHtml":"","embeddedInfographicUrl":"","embeddedType":"","geolocation":null,"headlineLong":"Google and Ogooglebar: Who owns the meaning of words?","headlineShort":"Who owns the meaning of words?","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageAltText":"","isSyndicated":false,"latitude":"","location":null,"longitude":"","mpsVideo":"","option":null,"partner":null,"primaryVertical":"future","promoAlignment":"centre","promoAltText":"","promoImage":null,"relatedStories":[],"relatedTag":null,"summaryLong":"Google's attempts to change the meaning of the word \"Ungoogleable\" in Sweden raises the question of who controls our language, says Tom Chatfield.","summaryShort":"...and why does Google care?","tag":[],"creationDateTime":"2014-11-18T09:14:40Z","entity":"article","guid":"4cd66fe1-b32a-4250-a856-13a742dff644","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20130328-who-owns-the-meaning-of-words","modifiedDateTime":"2019-10-04T14:34:19.621893Z","project":"future","slug":"20130328-who-owns-the-meaning-of-words","cacheLastUpdated":1587442999741},"future\u002Farticle\u002F20161129-the-new-words-that-reveal-how-tech-has-changed-us":{"urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:article:future\u002Farticle\u002F20161129-the-new-words-that-reveal-how-tech-has-changed-us","_id":"5e98209a272a584021ab04ee","ambientVideo":"","articleType":"story","assetVideo":null,"author":["future\u002Fauthor\u002Ftom-chatfield"],"bodyIntro":"Are you a phubber or a smombie? You're almost certainly a member of the bowed head tribe. New phrases can skewer our smartphone obsessions, says Tom Chatfield","businessUnit":"worldwide","cards":[{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"calloutBodyHtml":"\u003Cp\u003EChange happens quickly these days and it can be hard to keep up. That&rsquo;s why BBC Future has launched a new section called \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20161128-welcome-to-future-now\"\u003EFuture Now\u003C\u002Fa\u003E to bring you in-depth stories about the people, events and trends that are shaping our world.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EWe will be publishing regular stories from all over the world about technology, energy, economics, society and much more &ndash; \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fcolumns\u002Ffuture-now\"\u003Eyou can find them here\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. We hope you will join us as we explore the changes that matter.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E","calloutSubtitle":"Your essential guide to a world in flux","calloutTitle":"Welcome to Future Now","cardType":"CalloutBox","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20161129-the-new-words-that-reveal-how-tech-has-changed-us-0"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003ENew words sometimes skewer a trend so perfectly you wonder how you survived without them. One of the most delightfully apt new phrases I&rsquo;ve found in the last few years is a Chinese term: \u003Cem\u003Edī t&oacute;u z&uacute;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E (低頭族), literally the &ldquo;bowed head tribe&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWho does it describe? The people we see every day on city streets &ndash; or don&rsquo;t, because we&rsquo;re a member of the tribe ourselves &ndash; their heads lowered, gazing at their phones.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt&rsquo;s a wittier, more vivid description than &ldquo;smartphone addict&rdquo;. In tapping into the language of social types rather than medical pathology, it also feels a lot closer to our lived experience.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20161129-the-new-words-that-reveal-how-tech-has-changed-us-1"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p04jcjw2"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20161129-the-new-words-that-reveal-how-tech-has-changed-us-2"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EAnd if you belong to the bowed head tribe, you&rsquo;re probably an honorary member of the \u003Cem\u003Emǔ zhǐ z&uacute; \u003C\u002Fem\u003E(拇指) or &ldquo;thumb tribe&rdquo; too: someone whose two-digit tapping never stops. That term originated in Japan, where belonging to \u003Cem\u003Eoyayubizoku \u003C\u002Fem\u003E(拇指族) &ndash; the &ldquo;clan of the thumbs&rdquo; &ndash; was first coined to describe teenagers better at text messaging than talking.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20161129-the-new-words-that-reveal-how-tech-has-changed-us-3"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Competing notions of etiquette and appropriate behaviour are bubbling over into everyday speech","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20161129-the-new-words-that-reveal-how-tech-has-changed-us-4"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003ELike many social labels, these terms suggest disapproval of their subject, together with a wary recognition that change is afoot. Competing notions of etiquette and appropriate behaviour are bubbling over into everyday speech: an inter-tribal tension echoed across East Asian languages, as the Language Log blog has \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Flanguagelog.ldc.upenn.edu\u002Fnll\u002F?p=18108\"\u003Eexplored in some depth\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20161129-the-new-words-that-reveal-how-tech-has-changed-us-5"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p04jcjhz"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20161129-the-new-words-that-reveal-how-tech-has-changed-us-6"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EAre there Western equivalents? Two come to mind, although neither is quite as charming. The art of snubbing people by looking at your phone, even while you&rsquo;re buying a cup of coffee or sitting together at a table, is known as &ldquo;phubbing&rdquo;. Short for &ldquo;phone snubbing&rdquo; the word was coined in 2012 by Australian ad agency \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fmccann.com.au\u002Fproject\u002Fphubbing-a-word-is-born\u002F\"\u003EMcCann Melbourne\u003C\u002Fa\u003E as part of a dictionary promotion, which spawned a global &ldquo;\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fstopphubbing.com\u002F\"\u003Estop phubbing\u003C\u002Fa\u003E&rdquo; campaign.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMore sinister is the portmanteau &ldquo;smombie&rdquo;, short for &ldquo;smartphone zombie&rdquo; and used to describe a mindlessly strolling pedestrian whose attention is consumed by their device. Crowned \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.cafebabel.co.uk\u002Farticle\u002Fsmombie-the-unexpected-youth-word-of-the-year-2015.html\"\u003EYouth Word of the Year\u003C\u002Fa\u003E in Germany in 2015 &ndash; despite its general use by older speakers as a despairing description of young people &ndash; it took on new urgency with the Pokemon Go craze this summer. Germany also boasts the distinction of installing some of the world&rsquo;s \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.theguardian.com\u002Fcities\u002F2016\u002Fapr\u002F29\u002Falways-practise-safe-text-the-german-traffic-light-for-smartphone-zombies\"\u003Efirst traffic lights\u003C\u002Fa\u003E in the pavement, designed to stop smombies walking out in front of a bus.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20161129-the-new-words-that-reveal-how-tech-has-changed-us-7"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Terms of technological disapproval, conjured from hyperbolic hopes and fears, are as old as electronic communications","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20161129-the-new-words-that-reveal-how-tech-has-changed-us-8"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EIn a sense, none of this is new. Terms of technological disapproval, conjured from hyperbolic hopes and fears, are as old as electronic communications. When the telephone first arrived in American homes in the late 19th Century, it provoked both elation and despair.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor some, world peace was only a decade of international telephony away. For others, new forms of interaction meant new opportunities for addiction, timewasting and idle chat. Once again, new words needed to be found, and it was to the medical term &ldquo;mania&rdquo; that disconcerted commentators turned.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20161129-the-new-words-that-reveal-how-tech-has-changed-us-9"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p04jckmm"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20161129-the-new-words-that-reveal-how-tech-has-changed-us-10"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;The telephone maniacs,&rdquo; began an article in the Chicago journal \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Farchive.org\u002Fstream\u002Fwesternelectrici21chic\u002Fwesternelectrici21chic_djvu.txt\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003EWestern Electrician\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E on 17 July 1897, &ldquo;are usually men of leisure who have small appreciation of the value of time, and the more leisure they have the less hope there is for them, as far as cure is concerned&hellip; An unmistakable symptom of the disease is a desire to talk to people at distant points about all sorts of things at all hours of the day or night&hellip; The worst feature about the disease is that those who have it never realise that they are making themselves obnoxious, and, regardless of the hour or the pressure of business, they insist on telling long stories over the wire.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELong stories may since have turned into bouts of Facebook likes, but the urge to pour attention into distant delights at the expense of your immediate environment is stronger than ever. Indeed, it&rsquo;s a large part of the unfolding story of media, together with the challenge it poses to traditional ways of thinking about space, community and time.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20161129-the-new-words-that-reveal-how-tech-has-changed-us-11"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p04jcjlm"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20161129-the-new-words-that-reveal-how-tech-has-changed-us-12"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EWhat words will we need to describe someone walking through a cityscape adorned with augmented reality? And if you don&rsquo;t need to bow your head to view your screen &ndash; if it&rsquo;s built into glasses, worn as a contact lens or projected onto your retina &ndash; will anyone even be able to tell if they&rsquo;re being phubbed?\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBy then, perhaps, we&rsquo;ll need to specify not when our perceptions are machine-enhanced, but those rare times when they are not: when simply seeing what is under our noses demands a new word of its own.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fcolumns\u002Ffuture-now\"\u003E\u003Cimg src=\"http:\u002F\u002Fichef.bbci.co.uk\u002Fimages\u002Fic\u002Fraw\u002Fp04jj4t7.jpg\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Future Now\" width=\"100%\" \u002F\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003ETom Chatfield&rsquo;s book exploring technology and language, \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.barnesandnoble.com\u002Fw\u002Fnetymology-tom-chatfield\u002F1116412908?ean=9781623651640\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003ENetymology\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E, was published by Quercus US on 2 August.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Cem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Cem\u003EKeep up to date with Future Now stories by joining our 700,000+ fans on Facebook, or follow us on Twitter, Google+, LinkedIn and Instagram.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EIf you liked this story, sign up for the weekly bbc.com features newsletter, called &ldquo;If You Only Read 6 Things This Week&rdquo;. A handpicked selection of stories from BBC Future, Earth, Culture, Capital, Travel and Autos, delivered to your inbox every Friday.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20161129-the-new-words-that-reveal-how-tech-has-changed-us-13"}],"collection":["future\u002Fcolumn\u002Ffuture-now","future\u002Fpremium-collection\u002Ffuture-now"],"disableAdverts":false,"displayDate":"2016-11-29T14:55:15.949Z","embeddedCustomHtml":"","embeddedInfographicUrl":"","embeddedType":"","geolocation":null,"headlineLong":"The new words that expose our smartphone obsessions","headlineShort":"The new words for how we use our phones","image":["p04jcj00"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageAltText":"","isSyndicated":true,"latitude":"","location":null,"longitude":"","mpsVideo":"","option":[{"Content":{"Description":"Apple News Publish: Select to publish, remove to unpublish. (Do not just delete or unpublish the story)","Name":"publish-applenews-system-1"},"Metadata":{"CreationDateTime":"2016-02-05T14:32:31.186819Z","Entity":"option","Guid":"13f4bc85-ae27-4a34-9397-0e6ad3619619","Id":"option\u002Fpublish-applenews-system-1","ModifiedDateTime":"2016-02-05T14:32:31.186819Z","Project":"","Slug":"publish-applenews-system-1"},"Urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:option:option\u002Fpublish-applenews-system-1","_id":"5e98213a272a584021b09c21"}],"partner":null,"primaryVertical":"future","promoAlignment":"centre","promoAltText":"","promoImage":null,"relatedStories":["future\u002Far