003EThis story is featured in BBC Future&rsquo;s &ldquo;Best of 2016&rdquo; collection. \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fcolumns\u002Fbest-of-bbc-future\"\u003EDiscover more of our picks\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fli\u003E \u003C\u002Ful\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELet&rsquo;s face it, human sexuality is complicated. There are probably as many different sexual peccadilloes as there are flavours of food &ndash; and like our culinary tastes, our preferences vary from country to country, individual to individual, and day to day.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor this reason, trying to describe the &ldquo;normal&rdquo; sex life is something of a fool&rsquo;s errand; the variety is so great that a single statistic is never going to capture how most people feel. So BBC Future has looked at the data to try to get an idea of the full spread of the sexual spectrum &ndash; from how much we actually want sex to what we really do between the sheets.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENeedless to say, this comes with some serious caveats. Surveys of sexual behaviour are unreliable: given that talking about sex can still be taboo, participants may not reveal the whole truth, or, conversely, they may feel the need to embellish their answers with bravado. These statistics aren&rsquo;t the gospel truth, but should be read more as a general indication, given the evidence to date, of the range of sex lives in the 21st Century.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160217-what-is-a-normal-sex-life-0"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160217-what-is-a-normal-sex-life-1"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EIt&rsquo;s notoriously difficult to put a \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.cdc.gov\u002Fnchs\u002Fdata\u002Fnhsr\u002Fnhsr088.pdf\"\u003Efigure on sexual orientations\u003C\u002Fa\u003E: estimates of homosexuality vary from \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Flink.springer.com\u002Farticle\u002F10.1007\u002Fs10508-006-9088-5\"\u003E1% to 15%\u003C\u002Fa\u003E depending on whom you ask, how you ask it, and whether you are examining attraction, behaviour, or identity. Nevertheless, some recent surveys from across the world suggest that some people completely lack sexual desire (which is not to say they have never had a relationship). As with other sexual orientations, the exact prevalence is unknown (most settle around 1%) but there is a growing asexual pride movement for people who lack sexual feelings. Source: \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fsro.sussex.ac.uk\u002F49417\u002F\"\u003EPsychology and Sexuality\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160217-what-is-a-normal-sex-life-2"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160217-what-is-a-normal-sex-life-3"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EOne misconception is that most \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.psychologytoday.com\u002Fblog\u002Fstrictly-casual\u002F201408\u002Fwhat-type-casual-sex-are-people-really-having\"\u003Ecasual sex involves people we&rsquo;ve only just met\u003C\u002Fa\u003E; in reality, sex comes in many shades of informality, and the anonymous one-night-stand is relatively rare, as this US survey from 2009 showed. (Although that may be slightly skewed for the \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.sciencedirect.com\u002Fscience\u002Farticle\u002Fpii\u002FS1054139X12003515\"\u003Eyounger people\u003C\u002Fa\u003E in their teens and 20s, the figures are not so different for those aged up to 60.) In other words, for almost 50% of the population, &ldquo;it&rsquo;s complicated&rdquo;. Source: \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fonlinelibrary.wiley.com\u002Fdoi\u002F10.1111\u002Fj.1743-6109.2010.02020.x\u002Fpdf\"\u003