-stole-a-secret-soviet-fighter-jet":{"urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:article:future\u002Farticle\u002F20160905-the-pilot-who-stole-a-secret-soviet-fighter-jet","_id":"5e98209a272a584021ab039a","ambientVideo":"","articleType":"story","assetVideo":null,"author":[],"bodyIntro":"When pilot Viktor Belenko defected 40 years ago, he did so in a mysterious Soviet plane – the MiG-25. BBC Future investigates the far-reaching effects of one of the Cold War’s most intriguing events.","businessUnit":"worldwide","cards":[{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cul\u003E \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cem\u003EThis story is featured in BBC Future&rsquo;s &ldquo;Best of 2016&rdquo; collection. \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fcolumns\u002Fbest-of-bbc-future\"\u003EDiscover more of our picks\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fli\u003E \u003C\u002Ful\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn 6 September 1976, an aircraft appears out of the clouds near the Japanese city of Hakodate, on the northern island of Hokkaido. It&rsquo;s a twin-engined jet, but not the kind of short-haul airliner Hakodate is used to seeing. This huge, grey hulk sports the red stars of the Soviet Union. No-one in the West has ever seen one before.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe jet lands on Hakodate&rsquo;s concrete-and-asphalt runway. The runway, it turns out, is not long enough. The jet ploughs through hundreds of feet of earth before it finally comes to rest at the far end of the airport.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe pilot climbs out of the plane&rsquo;s cockpit and fires two warning shots from his pistol &ndash; motorists on the road next to the airport have been taking pictures of this strange sight. It is some minutes before airport officials, driving from the terminal, reach him. It is then that the 29-year-old pilot, Flight Lieutenant Viktor Ivanovich Belenko of the Soviet Air Defence Forces, announces that he wishes to defect.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is no normal defection. Belenko has not wandered into an embassy, or jumped ship while visiting a foreign port. The plane that he has flown 400-odd miles, and which now sits stranded at the end of a provincial Japanese runway, is the Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-25. It is the most secretive aircraft the Soviet Union has ever built.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUntil Belenko&rsquo;s landing, that is.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E--\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe West first became aware of what would become known as the MiG-25 around 1970. Spy satellites stalking Soviet airfields picked up a new kind of aircraft being tested in secret. They looked like enormous fighter planes, and the West&rsquo;s militaries were concerned by one particular feature; they sported very large wings.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160905-the-pilot-who-stole-a-secret-soviet-fighter-jet-0"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160905-the-pilot-who-stole-a-secret-soviet-fighter-jet-1"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EA large wing area is very useful in a fighter plane &ndash; it helps generate lift and it also decreases the amount of weight distributed across the wing, which helps make it more nimble and easier to turn. This Soviet jet seemed to combine this ability with a pair of enormous engines. How fast could it go? Could anything in the US Air Force or other militaries keep up with it?\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere had also been glimpses in the Middle East. In March 1971, Israel picked up a strange new aircraft that accelerated to Mach 3.2 &ndash; more than three times the speed of sound &ndash; and climbed to 63,000ft (nearly 20 kilometres). The Israelis, and US intelligence advisors, had never seen anything like it. Following a second sighting a few days later, Israeli fighters scrambled to intercept the aircraft but couldn&rsquo;t even come close.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160905-the-pilot-who-stole-a-secret-soviet-fighter-jet-2"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"The Pentagon put two and two together, and came up with a Cold War crisis","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160905-the-pilot-who-stole-a-secret-soviet-fighter-jet-3"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EIn November, the Israelis ambushed one of these mysterious intruders, firing missiles head on from 30,000ft below. It was a useless gesture. Their unidentified target streaked past at nearly three times the speed of sound &ndash; so fast the jet was already out of the danger zone by the time the missiles exploded.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Pentagon put two and two together, and came up with a Cold War crisis. They believed this jet was the same one that had been glimpsed from the satellite photos. They were suddenly presented with the prospect of a Soviet fighter that could outrun and out-turn anything in the US Air Force.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160905-the-pilot-who-stole-a-secret-soviet-fighter-jet-4"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160905-the-pilot-who-stole-a-secret-soviet-fighter-jet-5"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EIt was a classic case of military misinterpretation, says Stephen Trimble, the US editor of Flightglobal. &ldquo;They seemed to overestimate its abilities on pure appearance,&rdquo; he says, &ldquo;from the size of the wing and the huge size of its air intakes.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;They knew it would be very fast, and also thought it would be very manoeuvrable. They were right about the first one, but not so right about the second one.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhat the US satellites had seen, and the Israeli radars had tracked, were versions of the same aircraft &ndash; the MiG-25. It was built as a reaction to a series of aircraft the US were preparing to bring into service in the 1960s &ndash; from the \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fen.wikipedia.org\u002Fwiki\u002FNorth_American_XF-108_Rapier\"\u003EF-108 fighter plane\u003C\u002Fa\u003E to the \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20130701-flying-the-worlds-fastest-plane\"\u003ESR-71 spyplane\u003C\u002Fa\u003E and the massive \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fen.wikipedia.org\u002Fwiki\u002FNorth_American_XB-70_Valkyrie\"\u003EB-70 bomber\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. These aircraft all had one thing in common &ndash; they would fly at three times the speed of sound.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160905-the-pilot-who-stole-a-secret-soviet-fighter-jet-6"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"The technological leap needed to take an aircraft from Mach 2 to Mach 3 was an enormous challenge","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160905-the-pilot-who-stole-a-secret-soviet-fighter-jet-7"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EIn the 1950s, the Soviets had largely kept pace with the leapfrogging advances in aviation. They had bombers that could fly almost as fast and as high as the American B-52. Their fighter planes &ndash; many of which were made by the MiG design team &ndash; rivalled their American counterparts, though their radar and other electronics weren&rsquo;t quite so sophisticated.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBut the technological leap needed to take an aircraft from Mach 2 to Mach 3 was an enormous challenge. And this is what Soviet designers would have to do, as quickly as possible.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELed by MiG&rsquo;s brilliant Rostislav Belyakov, the design team set to work. To fly so fast, the new fighter would need engines pushing out colossal amounts of thrust. Tumansky, the leading engine designer of the USSR, had already built an engine they believed could do the job, the R-15 turbojet, which had been intended for a high-altitude cruise missile project. The new MiG would need two of them, each capable of pushing out 11 tonnes of thrust.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160905-the-pilot-who-stole-a-secret-soviet-fighter-jet-8"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160905-the-pilot-who-stole-a-secret-soviet-fighter-jet-9"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EFlying so fast creates enormous amounts of friction heat as the aircraft pushes against air molecules. When Lockheed built the SR-71 Blackbird, they built it out of titanium, which could withstand the enormous heat. But titanium is expensive and difficult to work with. Instead, MiG went with steel. And lots of it. The MiG-25 was welded together, by hand.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt&rsquo;s only when you stand next to a MiG-25 &ndash; and there are several spending their retirement parked on the grass at some of Russia&rsquo;s military museums &ndash; that you can fully appreciate just what a task it was. The MiG-25 is enormous. At 64ft (19.5m) long, it&rsquo;s only a few feet shorter than a World War Two-era Lancaster bomber. The airframe needed to be this big to accommodate the engines and the enormous amount of fuel needed to power them. &ldquo;The MiG-25 could carry something like 30,000lbs (13,600kg) of fuel,&rdquo; says Trimble.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThat heavy steel airframe was the reason the MiG-25 had such large wings &ndash; not to help it dogfight with US fighters, but simply in order to keep it in the air.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe MiGs were designed to take off and accelerate to Mach 2.5, guided to approaching targets by large, ground-based radars. When they were within 50 miles (80km), their own on-board radars would be able to take over, and they would fire their missiles &ndash; which, in keeping with the MiG&rsquo;s enormous size, were some 20-feet-long (6m).\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160905-the-pilot-who-stole-a-secret-soviet-fighter-jet-10"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"In the early 1970s, US defence chiefs knew nothing about the MiG&rsquo;s capabilities &ndash; though they had given it the codename &lsquo;Foxbat&rsquo;","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160905-the-pilot-who-stole-a-secret-soviet-fighter-jet-11"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EAs a counter to the American Blackbird, MiG also built a reconnaissance version, which was unarmed, but carried cameras and other sensors. Without the weight of the missiles and the targeting radar, this version was lighter &ndash; and it could fly as fast as Mach 3.2. This was the version spotted by Israel in 1971.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBut in the early 1970s, defence chiefs in the US knew nothing about the MiG&rsquo;s capabilities &ndash; though they had given it the codename &lsquo;Foxbat&rsquo;. They knew it only from blurred photos taken from space and from blips on radar screens above the Mediterranean. Unless they could somehow get their hands on one, it seemed that the MiG would remain a mysterious threat.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThat is, until a disillusioned Soviet fighter pilot hatched his plan.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E--\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EViktor Belenko had been a model Soviet citizen. He was born just after the end of World War Two, in the foothills of the Caucasus mountains. He entered military service and qualified as a fighter pilot &ndash; a role that brought with it certain perks compared to the average Soviet citizen.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160905-the-pilot-who-stole-a-secret-soviet-fighter-jet-12"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160905-the-pilot-who-stole-a-secret-soviet-fighter-jet-13"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EBut Belenko was disillusioned. The father-of-one was facing a divorce. He had started to question the very nature of Soviet society, and whether America was as evil as the Communist regime suggested. &ldquo;Soviet propaganda at that time portrayed you as a spoiled rotten society which has fallen apart,&rdquo; Belenko told \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.fullcontext.info\u002Fpeople\u002Fbelenko.htm\"\u003EFull Context magazine in 1996\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. &ldquo;But I had questions in my mind.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBelenko realised the huge new fighter he was training in might be his key to escape. He was based at the Chuguyevka Airbase in Primorsky Krai, near the far eastern city of Vladivostok. Japan was only 400 miles (644km) away. The new MiG could fly fast and it could fly high, but its two giant gas-guzzling engines meant it couldn&rsquo;t fly very far &ndash; certainly not far enough to land at a US airbase.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160905-the-pilot-who-stole-a-secret-soviet-fighter-jet-14"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"To evade both Soviet and Japanese military radar, Belenko had to fly very low &ndash; about 100ft above the sea","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160905-the-pilot-who-stole-a-secret-soviet-fighter-jet-15"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EOn 6 September Belenko flew off with fellow pilots on a training mission. None of the MiGs were armed. He had already worked out a rough route, and his MiG had a full tank of fuel.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe broke formation, and within a few minutes he was over the waves, heading towards Japan.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETo evade both Soviet and Japanese military radar, Belenko had to fly very low &ndash; about 100ft (30m) above the sea. When he was far enough into Japanese airspace, he took the MiG up to 20,000ft (6,000m) so it could be picked up by Japanese radar. The surprised Japanese tried to hail this unidentified aircraft, but Belenko&rsquo;s radio was tuned to the wrong frequencies. Japanese fighters were scrambled, but by then, Belenko had dropped below the thick cloud cover again. He disappeared off the Japanese radar screens.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAll this time, the Soviet pilot had been flying by guesswork, on the memory of maps he&rsquo;d studied before he&rsquo;d taken off. Belenko had intended to fly his aircraft to Chitose airbase, but with fuel running low, he had to land at the nearest available airport. That, as it turned out, was Hakdodate.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160905-the-pilot-who-stole-a-secret-soviet-fighter-jet-16"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"The Japanese suddenly found themselves with a defecting pilot &ndash; and a fighter jet that had so far evaded Western intelligence agencies","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160905-the-pilot-who-stole-a-secret-soviet-fighter-jet-17"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EJapan only really knew what they were dealing with when the MiG made its surprise landing.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Japanese suddenly found themselves with a defecting pilot &ndash; and a fighter jet that had so far evaded Western intelligence agencies. Hakodate&rsquo;s airport suddenly became a hive of intelligence activity. The CIA was scarcely able to believe its luck.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160905-the-pilot-who-stole-a-secret-soviet-fighter-jet-18"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160905-the-pilot-who-stole-a-secret-soviet-fighter-jet-19"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThe MiG was exhaustively examined after being moved to a nearby airbase.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;By disassembling the MiG-25 and inspecting it piece-by-piece over several weeks, they were able to understand exactly what they were capable of,&rdquo; says Trimble.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Soviets had not built the &lsquo;super-fighter&rsquo; the Pentagon had feared, says Smithsonian aviation curator Roger Connor, but an inflexible aircraft built to do a very particular job.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;The MiG-25 was not a very useful combat aircraft,&rdquo; says Connor. &ldquo;It was an expensive, and cumbersome aircraft, and it wasn&rsquo;t particularly effective in combat.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere were other problems too. Flying at Mach 3 meant enormous pressure on the engines. Lockheed&rsquo;s SR-71 had solved this by putting cones in the front of the engines, which slowed the air down enough so it didn&rsquo;t damage engine components. The air could then be forced out the back of the engine to help generate more thrust.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160905-the-pilot-who-stole-a-secret-soviet-fighter-jet-20"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"The MiG tracked at Mach 3.2 by Israel in 1971 essentially destroyed its engines in the process","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160905-the-pilot-who-stole-a-secret-soviet-fighter-jet-21"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThe MiG&rsquo;s turbojets generated thrust by sucking in air to help burn the fuel. Above 2,000mph (3,200km\u002Fh), however, things started to go wrong. The sheer force of the air could overwhelm the fuel pumps, dumping more and more fuel into the engine. And at the same time, the force exerted by the compressors would be so huge it would start sucking up parts of the engine. The MiG would start eating itself.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMiG-25 pilots were warned never to exceed Mach 2.8; the MiG tracked at Mach 3.2 by Israel in 1971 essentially destroyed its engines in the process, and was lucky to return to base.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160905-the-pilot-who-stole-a-secret-soviet-fighter-jet-22"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160905-the-pilot-who-stole-a-secret-soviet-fighter-jet-23"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThe spectre of the MiG-25 had caused the US to embark on a major new aircraft project &ndash; one that had helped create the F-15 Eagle, a fighter designed to be fast but also highly manoeuvrable like the MiG was thought to be. Forty years later, the F-15 is still in service.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn hindsight, the MiG, which the West had been so worried about, turned out to be a &lsquo;paper tiger&rsquo;. Its massive radar was years behind US models because instead of transistors it used antiquated vacuum tubes (a technology that did, however, make it impervious to electromagnetic pulses from nuclear blasts). The huge engines required so much fuel that the MiG was surprisingly short-ranged. It could take-off quickly, and fly in a straight line very fast to fire missiles or take pictures. That is about it.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe MiG that the Soviet Union had kept hidden from the world for several years was partially reassembled, and then loaded on a boat for its return to the USSR. The Japanese charged the Soviets a $40,000 bill for shipping costs and the damage Belenko had inflicted at Hakodate airport.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160905-the-pilot-who-stole-a-secret-soviet-fighter-jet-24"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"It&rsquo;s like Usain Bolt, except it&rsquo;s a Usain Bolt that&rsquo;s actually running slower than the marathon runner &ndash; Roger Connor, Smithsonian Air &amp; Space Museum","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160905-the-pilot-who-stole-a-secret-soviet-fighter-jet-25"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EIt soon became clear that the much-feared MiG was unable to intercept the US military&rsquo;s SR-71, one of the planes it was built to deal with.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;The one big difference between the MiG and the SR-71, is that the SR-71 is not only fast, but it&rsquo;s running a marathon,&rdquo; says Connor. &ldquo;The MiG is doing a sprint. It&rsquo;s like Usain Bolt, except it&rsquo;s a Usain Bolt that&rsquo;s actually running slower than the marathon runner.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese limitations didn&rsquo;t stop MiG building more than 1,200 MiG-25s. The &lsquo;Foxbat&rsquo; became a prestige plane for Soviet-backed air forces, who saw the propaganda value in fielding the second-fastest plane on Earth. Algeria and Syria are still thought to be flying them today. India used the reconnaissance model with great success for 25 years; they were only retired in 2006 because of a lack of spare parts.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe fear of the MiG-25 was its most impressive effect, says Trimble. &ldquo;Until 1976, [the US] didn&rsquo;t know that it wasn&rsquo;t capable of intercepting the SR-71, and that kept them out of Soviet airspace the entire period. The Soviets had been very sensitive to the idea of these overflights.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160905-the-pilot-who-stole-a-secret-soviet-fighter-jet-26"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160905-the-pilot-who-stole-a-secret-soviet-fighter-jet-27"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EBelenko himself did not return to the USSR with his partially dismantled fighter plane. The high-profile defector was allowed to move to the United States &ndash; his US citizenship personally approved by US president Jimmy Carter &ndash; where he become an aeronautics engineer and consultant to the US Air Force.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis military ID, and the notes he scribbled on a knee pad as he flew above the Sea of Japan are now on display at the \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.google.com\u002F?ion=1&amp;espv=2#q=cia%20museum%20viktor%20belenko\"\u003ECIA Museum\u003C\u002Fa\u003E in Washington DC.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe MiG-25&rsquo;s shortcomings, and the arrival of the American F-15, spurred Soviet designers to come up with new designs. Trimble says this eventually led to the Su-27 series designed by MiG&rsquo;s rival Sukhoi. It has been built in a myriad of ever-improving versions. It is exactly the kind of plane the Pentagon worried about at the beginning of the 1970s &ndash; fast and nimble &ndash; and the newer versions are probably the best fighter plane flying today, he says.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe MiG-25&rsquo;s story hasn&rsquo;t ended entirely either. The design was heavily modified to create the \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fgizmodo.com\u002Ftheres-no-threat-this-foxhound-cant-intercept-not-even-1594843910\"\u003EMiG-31\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, a fighter armed with sophisticated sensors, a powerful radar and better engines. &ldquo;The MiG-31 is essentially a full realisation of what the MiG-25 was supposed to be,&rdquo; says Trimble. The MiG-31 entered service a few years before the end of the Cold War, and hundreds still patrol Russia&rsquo;s vast borders. Western observers have had plenty of opportunities to see the MiG-31 at airshows, though much of their inner workings remain closely guarded.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter all, no Russian pilot has decided &ndash; for whatever reason &ndash; to seek exile outside of that vast country, and flown their MiG-31 to an unsuspecting foreign airfield.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EJoin 700,000+ Future fans by liking us on\u003C\u002Fem\u003E \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002FBBCFuture\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EFacebook\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E, or follow us on\u003C\u002Fem\u003E \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftwitter.com\u002Fbbc_future\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ETwitter\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E,\u003C\u002Fem\u003E \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fplus.google.com\u002F107828172298602173375\u002Fposts\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EGoogle+\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E,\u003C\u002Fem\u003E \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.linkedin.com\u002Fcompany\u002Fbbc-com\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ELinkedIn\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E \u003Cem\u003Eand \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Finstagram.com\u002Fbbcfuture_official\u002F\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EInstagram\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EIf you liked this story,&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fpages.emails.bbc.com\u002Fsubscribe\u002F\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003Esign up for the weekly bbc.com features newsletter\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E, called &ldquo;If You Only Read 6 Things This Week\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Cem\u003E&rdquo;. A handpicked selection of stories from BBC Future, Earth, Culture, Capital, Travel and Autos, delivered to your inbox every Friday.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160905-the-pilot-who-stole-a-secret-soviet-fighter-jet-28"}],"collection":[],"disableAdverts":false,"displayDate":"2016-09-05T16:53:51.405Z","embeddedCustomHtml":"","embeddedInfographicUrl":"","embeddedType":"","geolocation":null,"headlineLong":"The pilot who stole a secret Soviet fighter jet","headlineShort":"The pilot who stole a secret Soviet jet","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageAltText":"","isSyndicated":true,"latitude":"","location":null,"longitude":"","mpsVideo":"","option":[],"partner":null,"primaryVertical":"future","promoAlignment":"centre","promoAltText":"","promoImage":null,"relatedStories":[],"relatedTag":null,"summaryLong":"When pilot Viktor Belenko defected, he did so in a mysterious Soviet plane – the MiG-25. Stephen Dowling looks at its far-reaching impact.","summaryShort":"It was a defection that shook the world","tag":[],"creationDateTime":"2016-09-06T02:15:06.011753Z","entity":"article","guid":"e626f384-17f3-40cd-bc55-5ed0d02f1a0e","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160905-the-pilot-who-stole-a-secret-soviet-fighter-jet","modifiedDateTime":"2019-10-04T14:31:15.942132Z","project":"future","slug":"20160905-the-pilot-who-stole-a-secret-soviet-fighter-jet","cacheLastUpdated":1587442999743},"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160811-the-runaway-drone-that-caused-a-cold-war-air-battle":{"urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:article:future\u002Farticle\u002F20160811-the-runaway-drone-that-caused-a-cold-war-air-battle","_id":"5e982098272a584021aafe16","ambientVideo":"","articleType":"story","assetVideo":null,"author":[],"bodyIntro":"Sixty years ago, a violent air battle raged over the skies of Los Angeles – thanks to a runaway drone. BBC Future investigates the ‘Battle of Palmdale’.","businessUnit":"worldwide","cards":[{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EA decade after the end of World War II, US fighter planes were scrambled to protect the city of Los Angeles from an unexpected aerial threat. Nearby residents would soon run for cover as rockets rained down on American soil. The threat wasn&rsquo;t from Soviet intruders. And the pilots did not succeed in their mission. It&rsquo;s now known by some as the Battle of Palmdale.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis is what happened that Thursday morning exactly 60 years ago &ndash; and why the danger is still with us six decades on.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAt 11.34am on Thursday 16 August 1956, a special aircraft was launched from a naval air station in California. It was a Grumman F6F Hellcat fighter plane, but refitted as an unmanned vehicle &ndash; a drone. Painted bright red, it was about to be used as a target during a missile test. It would take off and fly at a leisurely pace over the Pacific Ocean before being blown to smithereens. At least, that was the plan.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160811-the-runaway-drone-that-caused-a-cold-war-air-battle-0"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160811-the-runaway-drone-that-caused-a-cold-war-air-battle-1"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EInstead of taking the desired course, the drone stopped responding to commands from its remote controllers and veered southeast, towards the huge city of Los Angeles. It was an immediate danger &ndash; a crash in the wrong place could be lethal. Navy officers quickly got on the phone to nearby Oxnard Air Force Base, which had pilots on alert in case of a Russian bomber attack. Two fighters were scrambled to chase the drone, which was now nearing the city.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs the fighter pilots caught up with it, the Hellcat crossed over Los Angeles&rsquo; airspace and eventually into an area above unpopulated land. This was their first chance. The pilots&rsquo; F-89D Scorpions were equipped with &ldquo;Mighty Mouse&rdquo; rockets. They were unguided rockets, armed with an explosive warhead, and could easily take down a drone of the target&rsquo;s size &ndash; if they scored a direct hit.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160811-the-runaway-drone-that-caused-a-cold-war-air-battle-2"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"All along the flight path of the fighters and their bright red quarry lay destruction caused by the F-89s&rsquo; wayward salvoes","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160811-the-runaway-drone-that-caused-a-cold-war-air-battle-3"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EBut there was a problem. The rockets failed to launch when the pilots first attempted to fire them using an automatic system &ndash; they would have to switch to manual. But at that point the drone changed its course again, this time back towards Los Angeles. The situation was becoming more urgent. An initial volley of 42 rockets was fired, to no avail. The second plane fired another 42 &ndash; still no hit. The drone was now nearing a suburban town called Newhall. Another volley. All the rockets missed.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFinally, as the drone turned in the direction of Palmdale, each plane fired off another round of rockets &ndash; this time 30 each. It was their last chance. But every rocket missed; 208 rockets fired and no luck. The drone flew on but ran out of fuel. Eventually, it crashed eight miles east of Palmdale, cutting through electric cables as it ploughed into the ground.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIncredibly, no-one was hurt or killed. But all those rockets hadn&rsquo;t landed without incident. All along the flight path of the fighters and their bright red quarry lay destruction caused by the F-89s&rsquo; wayward salvoes. The newspapers of the day reveal the full extent of the damage.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160811-the-runaway-drone-that-caused-a-cold-war-air-battle-4"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160811-the-runaway-drone-that-caused-a-cold-war-air-battle-5"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EFires raged across 350 acres near Newhall &ndash; and it took hundreds of firemen to deal with them. Shrapnel burst through windows and into homes. One teenager driving in Palmdale had debris blast through his windshield; luckily he escaped unscathed.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOne newspaper wryly wrote up the consequences of an &ldquo;unintentional bombing attack&rdquo; while the Los Angeles Times described as best it could the &ldquo;uncontrolled and dangerous circle&rdquo; of the drone&rsquo;s flight.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMany of the rockets hit the ground without exploding, but there was every chance that a slight disturbance could set them off. The US Air Force circulated a description of the weapons to residents in an attempt to avoid any fatal accidents.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160811-the-runaway-drone-that-caused-a-cold-war-air-battle-6"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"In 1997, Merlin and fellow investigator Tony Moore managed to find the Hellcat&rsquo;s crash site","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160811-the-runaway-drone-that-caused-a-cold-war-air-battle-7"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;It was just such a bizarre story,&rdquo; says aviation archaeologist Peter Merlin, who stumbled across the incident 20 years ago. He had been reading some old local newspapers from the era while researching aircraft experiments and unexpectedly discovered the tale of the runaway Hellcat.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt wasn&rsquo;t the first time the remote-controlled Hellcats had been used. &nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;They used some of them during atomic bomb tests, to fly the drones into atomic clouds and collect samples,&rdquo; explains Merlin.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160811-the-runaway-drone-that-caused-a-cold-war-air-battle-8"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160811-the-runaway-drone-that-caused-a-cold-war-air-battle-9"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EMerlin is fascinated with the number of military aircraft that flew in California at this time. Indeed, he&rsquo;s amassed a list of 700 crash sites since the 1930s. &ldquo;Most of them are military or experimental planes,&rdquo; he says.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn 1997, Merlin and fellow investigator Tony Moore managed to find the Hellcat&rsquo;s crash site. He says they could even see the scars of damage still left on the repaired powerlines. And in the dirt were obvious pieces of aluminium &ndash; with red paint and markings proving it was indeed the aircraft they were looking for.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhy couldn&rsquo;t the Air Force fighters shoot the thing down, then, especially after so many attempts? As Doug Barrie of the International Institute for Strategic Studies in London says, the task was a lot easier said than done.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160811-the-runaway-drone-that-caused-a-cold-war-air-battle-10"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"It&rsquo;s not the easiest thing in the world to do and the more you miss, the harder it gets &ndash; Doug Barrie, International Institute for Strategic Studies","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160811-the-runaway-drone-that-caused-a-cold-war-air-battle-11"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;You&rsquo;ve got these two vehicles moving in three dimensions and you&rsquo;re firing an unguided rocket which is itself moving along at a fair old lick,&rdquo; he says.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;It&rsquo;s not the easiest thing in the world to do and the more you miss, the harder it gets.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFiring a salvo of rockets into an enemy bomber formation was one thing, it seems, but trying to hit a small single target was quite another, as the Air Force found out that day.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160811-the-runaway-drone-that-caused-a-cold-war-air-battle-12"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160811-the-runaway-drone-that-caused-a-cold-war-air-battle-13"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003ECould something similar happen now? Barrie says it could, but there are more safeguards in place.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor one thing, remotely guided weapons and vehicles are often equipped with self-destruct mechanisms should they go awry.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;And if the data link is lost for any amount of time you have a number of options &ndash; one of which is for the UAV to enter a loiter pattern so that it can attempt to reacquire the data link,&rdquo; says Barrie.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;If that doesn&rsquo;t happen within enough time and it has enough fuel, it will attempt to return to base.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Palmdale incident certainly isn&rsquo;t the only example of a runaway aircraft littering the annals of military history. In 2009, the Air Force had better success in shooting down a runaway drone &ndash; this time a modern Reaper &ndash; that \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.popsci.com\u002Fmilitary-aviation-amp-space\u002Farticle\u002F2009-09\u002Fwhen-drones-go-wild-air-force-shoots-them-down\"\u003Enearly flew out of Afghan airspace\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160811-the-runaway-drone-that-caused-a-cold-war-air-battle-14"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"A more tragic case occurred in 1989, when a Soviet pilot ejected from a MiG-23 fighter","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160811-the-runaway-drone-that-caused-a-cold-war-air-battle-15"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EAnd manned aircraft can sometimes wriggle out of human control, too. In 1970, a Convair F-106 jet went into a spin over Montana, prompting the pilot to eject. Amazingly, the plane stabilised and \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fen.wikipedia.org\u002Fwiki\u002FConvair_F-106_Delta_Dart#The_Cornfield_Bomber\"\u003Elanded in a snowy field\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. It was in such good condition that, following repairs, it was returned to service. It earned the nickname &ldquo;The Cornfield Bomber&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBut a more tragic case occurred in 1989, when a Soviet pilot ejected from a MiG-23 fighter that seemed to have suffered power loss. At that point the jet was in Polish airspace, but following the ejection it continued to fly on autopilot towards the West.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt flew right over East and then West Germany. US Air Force pilots were scrambled from a base in the Netherlands and told to shoot the MiG down over the North Sea. But before it reached that point, the wayward aircraft ran low on fuel, turned south and eventually crashed into a house &ndash; killing a Belgian teenager.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;Technology,&rdquo; says Barrie, &ldquo;is fallible&rdquo;. And it probably always will be.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160811-the-runaway-drone-that-caused-a-cold-war-air-battle-16"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160811-the-runaway-drone-that-caused-a-cold-war-air-battle-17"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EBut Merlin, who is more aware than most of how accident-prone the development of these machines can be, points out that failures have always been a part of aviation history.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;The area where I live is full of aviation history &ndash; experimental vehicles, X-planes, the development of the Space Shuttle &ndash; so many different things were done out here,&rdquo; he says.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;There was a very steep learning curve so crash sites kind of represent that legacy.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThankfully, the Battle of Palmdale, as it was later dubbed, did not result in any deaths. But it certainly was extraordinary. A contest between man and a machine with a mind of its own, 60 years ago &ndash; in the bright blue skies above Los Angeles.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EJoin 600,000+ Future fans by liking us on\u003C\u002Fem\u003E \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002FBBCFuture\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EFacebook\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E, or follow us on\u003C\u002Fem\u003E \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftwitter.com\u002Fbbc_future\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ETwitter\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E,\u003C\u002Fem\u003E \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fplus.google.com\u002F107828172298602173375\u002Fposts\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EGoogle+\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E,\u003C\u002Fem\u003E \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.linkedin.com\u002Fcompany\u002Fbbc-com\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ELinkedIn\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E \u003Cem\u003Eand \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Finstagram.com\u002Fbbcfuture_official\u002F\"\u00