her crops","tag":[],"creationDateTime":"2015-12-28T08:45:00.122074Z","entity":"article","guid":"28fc01f9-7209-4f02-9934-0688b4f00ff5","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20151228-heres-how-climate-change-will-affect-what-you-eat","modifiedDateTime":"2019-10-04T14:32:01.111235Z","project":"future","slug":"20151228-heres-how-climate-change-will-affect-what-you-eat","cacheLastUpdated":1587442999746},"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160926-what-would-happen-if-the-world-suddenly-went-vegetarian":{"urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:article:future\u002Farticle\u002F20160926-what-would-happen-if-the-world-suddenly-went-vegetarian","_id":"5e9820a7f363927515d0e378","ambientVideo":"","articleType":"story","assetVideo":null,"author":["future\u002Fauthor\u002Frachel-nuwer"],"bodyIntro":"Eliminating meat from our diets would bring a bounty of benefits to both our own health and the planet’s – but it could also harm millions of people.","businessUnit":"worldwide","cards":[{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EPeople become vegetarians for a variety of reasons. Some do it to alleviate animal suffering, others because they want to pursue a healthier lifestyle. Still others are fans of sustainability or wish to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENo matter how much their carnivorous friends might deny it, vegetarians have a point: cutting out meat delivers multiple benefits. And the more who make the switch, the more those perks would manifest on a global scale.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBut if everyone became a committed vegetarian, there would be serious drawbacks for millions, if not billions, of people.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;It&rsquo;s a tale of two worlds, really,&rdquo; says \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fccafs.cgiar.org\u002Fabout\u002Fwho-we-are\u002Four-staff\u002Fresearchers\u002Ftheme-leader\u002Fandrew-jarvis#.V6n_wJMrLow\"\u003EAndrew Jarvis\u003C\u002Fa\u003E of Colombia&rsquo;s International Centre for Tropical Agriculture. &ldquo;In developed countries, vegetarianism would bring all sorts of environmental and health benefits. But in developing countries there would be negative effects in terms of poverty.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160926-what-would-happen-if-the-world-suddenly-went-vegetarian-0"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p0494gk5"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160926-what-would-happen-if-the-world-suddenly-went-vegetarian-1"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EJarvis and other experts at the centre hypothesised what might happen if meat dropped off the planet&rsquo;s menu overnight.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFirst, they examined climate change. Food production accounts for one-quarter to \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.earth-syst-sci-data.net\u002F7\u002F47\u002F2015\u002F\"\u003Eone-third\u003C\u002Fa\u003E of all anthropogenic greenhouse gas emissions worldwide, and the brunt of responsibility for those numbers falls to the livestock industry. Despite this, how our dietary choices affect climate change is often underestimated. In the US, for example, an average family of four emits \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.foodsecurity.ac.uk\u002Fblog\u002F2014\u002F10\u002Fcars-cows-and-carbon\u002F\"\u003Emore greenhouse gases\u003C\u002Fa\u003E because of the meat they eat than from driving two cars &ndash; but it is cars, not steaks, that regularly come up in discussions about global warming.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160926-what-would-happen-if-the-world-suddenly-went-vegetarian-2"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Most people don&rsquo;t think of the consequences of food on climate change &ndash; Tim Benton","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160926-what-would-happen-if-the-world-suddenly-went-vegetarian-3"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;Most people don&rsquo;t think of the consequences of food on climate change,&rdquo; says \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.fbs.leeds.ac.uk\u002Fstaff\u002Fprofile.php?tag=Benton_T\"\u003ETim Benton\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, a food security expert at the University of Leeds. &ldquo;But just eating a little less meat right now might make things a whole lot better for our children and grandchildren.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.futureoffood.ox.ac.uk\u002Fpeople\u002Fmarco-springmann\"\u003EMarco Springmann\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, a research fellow at the Oxford Martin School&rsquo;s Future of Food programme, tried to quantify just how much better: he and his colleagues built computer models that predicted what would happen if everyone became vegetarian by 2050. \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.pnas.org\u002Fcontent\u002F113\u002F15\u002F4146.full\"\u003EThe results\u003C\u002Fa\u003E indicate that &ndash; largely thanks to the elimination of red meat &ndash; food-related emissions would drop by about 60%. If the world went vegan instead, emissions declines would be around 70%.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;When looking at what would be in line with avoiding dangerous levels of climate change, we found that you could only stabilise the ratio of food-related emissions to all emissions if everyone adopted a plant-based diet,&rdquo; Springmann says. &ldquo;That scenario is not very realistic &ndash; but it highlights the importance that food-related emissions will play in the future.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160926-what-would-happen-if-the-world-suddenly-went-vegetarian-4"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p0494f26"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160926-what-would-happen-if-the-world-suddenly-went-vegetarian-5"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EFood, especially livestock, also takes up a lot of room &ndash; a source of both greenhouse gas emissions due to land conversion and of biodiversity loss. Of the world&rsquo;s approximately five billion hectares (12 billion acres) of agricultural land, \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.fao.org\u002Fdocrep\u002F010\u002Fa0701e\u002Fa0701e00.HTM\"\u003E68% is used for livestock\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160926-what-would-happen-if-the-world-suddenly-went-vegetarian-6"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"If everyone became vegetarian by 2050, food-related emissions would drop by 60%","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160926-what-would-happen-if-the-world-suddenly-went-vegetarian-7"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EShould we all go vegetarian, ideally we would dedicate at least 80% of that pastureland to the restoration of grasslands and forests, which would capture carbon and further alleviate climate change. Converting former pastures to native habitats would likely also be a boon to biodiversity, including for large herbivores such as buffalo that were pushed out for cattle, as well as for predators like wolves that are often killed in retaliation for attacking livestock.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe remaining 10 to 20% of former pastureland could be used for growing more crops to fill gaps in the food supply. Though a relatively small increase in agricultural land, this would more than make up for the loss of meat because one-third of the land currently used for crops is dedicated to producing food for livestock &ndash; not for humans.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBoth environmental restoration and conversion to plant-based agriculture would require planning and investment, however, given than pasturelands tend to be highly degraded. &ldquo;You couldn&rsquo;t just take cows off the land and expect it to become a primary forest again on its own,&rdquo; Jarvis says.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarnivorous careers\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPeople formerly engaged in the livestock industry would also need assistance transitioning to a new career, whether in agriculture, helping with reforestation or producing bioenergy from crop byproducts currently used as livestock feed.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESome farmers could also be paid to keep livestock for environmental purposes. &ldquo;I&rsquo;m sitting here in Scotland where the Highlands environment is very manmade and based largely on grazing by sheep,&rdquo; says \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.research.ed.ac.uk\u002Fportal\u002Fen\u002Fpersons\u002Fpeter-alexander(53951c2f-6d8f-403a-b683-b04fdb553ac1).html\"\u003EPeter Alexander\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, a researcher in socio-ecological systems modelling at the University of Edinburgh. &ldquo;If we took all the sheep away, the environment would look different and there would be a potential negative impact on biodiversity.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShould we fail to provide clear career alternatives and subsidies for former livestock-related employees, meanwhile, we would probably face significant unemployment and social upheaval &ndash; especially in rural communities with close ties to the industry.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160926-what-would-happen-if-the-world-suddenly-went-vegetarian-8"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p0494gw6"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160926-what-would-happen-if-the-world-suddenly-went-vegetarian-9"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;There are over 3.5 billion domestic ruminants on earth, and tens of billions of chickens produced and killed each year for food,&rdquo; says \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.zoo.cam.ac.uk\u002Fdirectory\u002Fben-phalan\"\u003EBen Phalan\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, who researches the balance between food demand and biodiversity at the University of Cambridge. &ldquo;We&rsquo;d be talking about a huge amount of economic disruption.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBut even the best-laid plans probably wouldn&rsquo;t be able to offer alternative livelihoods for everyone. Around one-third of the world&rsquo;s land is composed of arid and semi-arid rangeland that can only support animal agriculture. In the past, when people have attempted to convert parts of the Sahel &ndash; a massive east-to-west strip of Africa located south of the Sahara and north of the equator &ndash; from livestock pasture to croplands, desertification and loss of productivity have ensued. &ldquo;Without livestock, life in certain environments would likely become impossible for some people,&rdquo; Phalan says. That especially includes nomadic groups such as the Mongols and Berbers who, stripped of their livestock, would have to settle permanently in cities or towns &ndash; likely losing their cultural identity in the process.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlus, even those whose entire livelihoods do not depend on livestock would stand to suffer. Meat is an important part of history, tradition and cultural identity. Numerous groups around the world give livestock gifts at weddings, celebratory dinners such as Christmas centre around turkey or roast beef, and meat-based dishes are emblematic of certain regions and people. &ldquo;The cultural impact of completely giving up meat would be very big, which is why efforts to reduce meat consumption have often faltered,&rdquo; Phalan says.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160926-what-would-happen-if-the-world-suddenly-went-vegetarian-10"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Worldwide vegetarianism by 2050 would lead to a global mortality reduction of up to 10%","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160926-what-would-happen-if-the-world-suddenly-went-vegetarian-11"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThe effect on health is mixed, too. Springmann&rsquo;s computer model study showed that, should everyone go vegetarian by 2050, we would see a global mortality reduction of 6-10%, thanks to a lessening of coronary heart disease, diabetes, stroke and some cancers. Eliminating red meat accounts for half of that decline, while the remaining benefits are thanks to scaling back the number of calories people consume and increasing the amount of fruit and vegetables they eat. A worldwide vegan diet would further amplify these benefits: global vegetarianism would stave off about 7 million deaths per year, while total veganism would knock that estimate up to 8 million. Fewer people suffering from food-related chronic illnesses would also mean a reduction in medical bills, saving about 2-3% of global gross domestic product.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160926-what-would-happen-if-the-world-suddenly-went-vegetarian-12"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p0494h40"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160926-what-would-happen-if-the-world-suddenly-went-vegetarian-13"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EBut realising these projected benefits would require replacing meat with nutritionally appropriate substitutes. Animal products contain more nutrients per calorie than vegetarian staples like grains and rice, so choosing the right replacement would be important, especially for the world&rsquo;s estimated \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Flink.springer.com\u002Farticle\u002F10.1007\u002Fs12571-008-0002-y\"\u003Etwo billion-plus\u003C\u002Fa\u003E undernourished people. &ldquo;Going vegetarian globally could create a health crisis in the developing world, because where would the micronutrients come from?&rdquo; Benton says.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAll in moderation\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBut fortunately, the entire world doesn&rsquo;t need to convert to vegetarianism or veganism to reap many of the benefits while limiting the repercussions.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInstead, moderation in meat-eating&rsquo;s frequency and portion size is key. \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Flink.springer.com\u002Farticle\u002F10.1007\u002Fs10584-015-1329-y\"\u003EOne study\u003C\u002Fa\u003E found that simply conforming to the World Health Organization&rsquo;s dietary recommendations would bring the UK&rsquo;s greenhouse gas emissions down by 17% &ndash; a figure that would drop by an additional 40% should citizens further avoid animal products and processed snacks. &ldquo;These are dietary changes that consumers would barely notice, like having a just-slightly-smaller piece of meat,&rdquo; Jarvis says. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s not this either-or, vegetarian-or-carnivore scenario.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECertain changes to the food system also would encourage us all to make healthier and more environmentally-friendly dietary decisions, says Springmann &ndash; like putting a higher price tag on meat and making fresh fruits and vegetables cheaper and more widely available. Addressing inefficiency would also help: thanks to food loss, waste and overeating, fewer than 50% of the calories currently produced are actually used effectively.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;There is a way to have low productivity systems that are high in animal and environmental welfare &ndash; as well as profitable &ndash; because they&rsquo;re producing meat as a treat rather than a daily staple,&rdquo; Benton says. &ldquo;In this situation, farmers get the exact same income. They&rsquo;re just growing animals in a completely different way.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn fact, \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.fao.org\u002F3\u002Fi3437e.pdf\"\u003Eclear solutions\u003C\u002Fa\u003E already exist for reducing greenhouse gas emissions from the livestock industry. What is lacking is the will to implement those changes.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EJoin 700,000+ Future fans by liking us on \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002FBBCFuture\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003EFacebook\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E, or follow us on \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftwitter.com\u002Fbbc_future\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003ETwitter\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E, \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fplus.google.com\u002F107828172298602173375\u002Fposts\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003EGoogle+\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E, \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.linkedin.com\u002Fcompany\u002Fbbc-com\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003ELinkedIn\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E and \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Finstagram.com\u002Fbbcfuture_official\u002F\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003EInstagram\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EIf you liked this story,&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fpages.emails.bbc.com\u002Fsubscribe\u002F?ocid=fut.bbc.email.we.email-signup\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003Esign up for the weekly bbc.com features newsletter\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E, called &ldquo;If You Only Read 6 Things This Week&rdquo;. A handpicked selection of stories from BBC Future, Earth, Culture, Capital, Travel and Autos, delivered to your inbox every Friday.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160926-what-would-happen-if-the-world-suddenly-went-vegetarian-14"}],"collection":["future\u002Fcolumn\u002Fwhat-if","future\u002Fcolumn\u002Fbest-of-bbc-future"],"disableAdverts":false,"displayDate":"2016-09-27T00:31:15Z","embeddedCustomHtml":"","embeddedInfographicUrl":"","embeddedType":"","geolocation":null,"headlineLong":"What would happen if the world suddenly went vegetarian?","headlineShort":"What if the world went vegetarian?","image":["p0494gy5"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageAltText":"","isSyndicated":true,"latitude":"","location":null,"longitude":"","mpsVideo":"","option":[{"Content":{"Description":"Apple News Publish: Select to publish, remove to unpublish. (Do not just delete or unpublish the story)","Name":"publish-applenews-system-1"},"Metadata":{"CreationDateTime":"2016-02-05T14:32:31.186819Z","Entity":"option","Guid":"13f4bc85-ae27-4a34-9397-0e6ad3619619","Id":"option\u002Fpublish-applenews-system-1","ModifiedDateTime":"2016-02-05T14:32:31.186819Z","Project":"","Slug":"publish-applenews-system-1"},"Urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:option:option\u002Fpublish-applenews-system-1","_id":"5e98213a272a584021b09c21"}],"partner":null,"primaryVertical":"future","promoAlignment":"centre","promoAltText":"","promoImage":["p0494gk5"],"relatedStories":["future\u002Farticle\u002F20160824-what-would-happen-if-all-animals-were-as-smart-as-us","future\u002Farticle\u002F20160424-if-cryonics-suddenly-worked-wed-need-to-face-the-fallout","future\u002Farticle\u002F20160922-the-nut-that-helped-to-build-a-global-empire","future\u002Farticle\u002F20141127-the-last-unmapped-places","future\u002Farticle\u002F20151228-heres-how-climate-change-will-affect-what-you-eat"],"relatedTag":null,"summaryLong":"Eliminating meat from our diets would bring a bounty of benefits to both our own health and the planet’s – but it could also harm millions of people. Rachel Nuwer investigates.","summaryShort":"The unanticipated consequences if everyone gave up meat","tag":["tag\u002Ffood"],"creationDateTime":"2016-09-27T01:52:29.545167Z","entity":"article","guid":"cfba3b61-09d6-4102-af96-984387ca6852","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20160926-what-would-happen-if-the-world-suddenly-went-vegetarian","modifiedDateTime":"2019-10-04T14:28:53.945442Z","project":"future","slug":"20160926-what-would-happen-if-the-world-suddenly-went-vegetarian","cacheLastUpdated":1587443000191},"future\u002Farticle\u002F20170207-what-if-the-internet-stopped-for-a-day":{"urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:article:future\u002Farticle\u002F20170207-what-if-the-internet-stopped-for-a-day","_id":"5e982099272a584021aaff9b","ambientVideo":"","articleType":"story","assetVideo":null,"author":["future\u002Fauthor\u002Frachel-nuwer"],"bodyIntro":"For many people, going without the internet even for a few hours is unthinkable. But if it did stop working, the impact might not be what you'd expect.","businessUnit":"worldwide","cards":[{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fcomm.stanford.edu\u002Ffaculty-hancock\u002F\"\u003EJeff Hancock\u003C\u002Fa\u003E likes to give his Stanford University students weekend assignments that let them experience concepts discussed in class for themselves. Before 2008, he would sometimes challenge his students to stay off the internet for 48 hours and then discuss how it affected them. But when Hancock returned to work in 2009, after a year-long sabbatical, things had changed.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;When I tried to introduce the task, there was a class revolt,&rdquo; says Hancock, who studies the psychological and social processes involved in online communication. &ldquo;The students emphatically said the assignment was impossible and unfair.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThey argued that going offline even for a weekend would prevent them from completing work in other classes, ruin their social lives, and make their friends and family worry that something terrible had happened to them. Hancock had to concede and cancelled the activity &ndash; and he&rsquo;s never attempted it again. &ldquo;That was 2009, and now with mobile as present as it is, I don&rsquo;t even know what students would do if I asked them to do that,&rdquo; he says. &ldquo;They&rsquo;d probably report me to the university president.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20170207-what-if-the-internet-stopped-for-a-day-0"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p04s7451"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20170207-what-if-the-internet-stopped-for-a-day-1"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EBut with our always-connected lifestyles, the question is now more relevant than ever: what would happen if the internet stopped for a day? It turns out the impact might not be quite what you'd expect.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn 1995, \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.internetlivestats.com\u002Finternet-users\u002F\"\u003Efewer than 1% of the world&rsquo;s population was online\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. The internet was a curiosity, used mostly by people in the West. Fast-forward 20 years and today more than 3.5bn people have an internet connection &ndash; nearly half of all humans on the planet &ndash; and the number is growing at a rate of around 10 people a second.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAccording to the Pew Research Centre, \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.pewresearch.org\u002Ffact-tank\u002F2015\u002F12\u002F08\u002Fone-fifth-of-americans-report-going-online-almost-constantly\u002F\"\u003Ea fifth of all Americans say they use the internet &ldquo;almost constantly&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fa\u003E and 73% say they use it at least daily. Figures in the UK are similar: a 2016 survey found that \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ons.gov.uk\u002Fbusinessindustryandtrade\u002Fitandinternetindustry\u002Fbulletins\u002Finternetusers\u002F2016\"\u003Enearly 90% of adults said they had used the internet in the previous three months\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. For many, it is now virtually impossible to imagine life without the internet.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;One of the biggest problems with the internet today is that people take it for granted &ndash; yet they don&rsquo;t understand the degree to which we&rsquo;ve allowed it to infiltrate almost every aspect of our lives,&rdquo; says \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fcas.msu.edu\u002Fpeople\u002Ffaculty-staff\u002Fstaff-listing\u002Fname\u002Fwilliam-dutton\u002F\"\u003EWilliam Dutton\u003C\u002Fa\u003E at Michigan State University, who is the author of the book Society and the Internet. &ldquo;They don&rsquo;t even think about not having access to it.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20170207-what-if-the-internet-stopped-for-a-day-2"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"I don&rsquo;t know what students today would do if I asked them to stay off the internet &ndash; they&rsquo;d probably report me to the university president &ndash; Jeff Hancock","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20170207-what-if-the-internet-stopped-for-a-day-3"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EBut the internet is not inviolable. In theory, it could be taken away, on a global or national scale, for a stretch of time. Cyberattacks are one possibility. Malicious hackers could bring the internet to a standstill by releasing software that aggressively targeted vulnerabilities in routers &ndash; the devices that forward internet traffic. Shutting down domain name servers &ndash; the internet&rsquo;s address books &ndash; would also cause massive disruption, preventing websites from loading, for example.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECutting the deep-sea cables that carry vast volumes of internet traffic between continents would also cause significant disruptions by disconnecting one part of the world from another. These cables may not be easy targets for attackers, but they are sometimes damaged accidentally. In 2008, people in the Middle East, India and Southeast Asia were plagued by major internet outages on three separate occasions when submarine cables were cut or interfered with.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESome governments also have &ldquo;kill switches&rdquo; that can effectively turn off the internet in their country. Egypt did this during the Arab Spring uprising in 2011 to make it more difficult for protesters to coordinate their activity. Turkey and Iran have also shut off internet connectivity during protests. China is rumoured to have a kill switch of its own. And American \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fusatoday30.usatoday.com\u002Ftech\u002Fnews\u002Finternetprivacy\u002F2011-02-15-kill-switch_N.htm\"\u003Esenators have proposed creating one in the US\u003C\u002Fa\u003E as a means to defend the country from cyberattack.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBuilding a kill switch is not easy, however. The larger and more developed the country, the harder it is to shut down the internet completely &shy;&ndash; there are simply too many connections between networks both inside and outside national borders.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20170207-what-if-the-internet-stopped-for-a-day-4"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p04s73y2"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20170207-what-if-the-internet-stopped-for-a-day-5"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most devastating strikes could come from space, however. A large solar storm that sent flares in our direction \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.nasa.gov\u002Ftopics\u002Fearth\u002Ffeatures\u002Fsun_darkness.html\"\u003Ewould take out satellites, power grids and computer systems\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. &ldquo;What bombs and terrorism can&rsquo;t do might be accomplished in moments by a solar flare,&rdquo; says \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.eagleman.com\u002F\"\u003EDavid Eagleman\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, a neuroscientist at Stanford University and author of Why the Net Matters. &ldquo;The next major geomagnetic storms are eventually coming.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBut most outages would not last long. &ldquo;There&rsquo;s an army of people ready to put things right,&rdquo; says \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.usccu.us\u002F\"\u003EScott Borg\u003C\u002Fa\u003E at the United States Cyber Consequences Unit, a non-profit organisation. &ldquo;The internet service providers and the companies that make the routing equipment have plans and personnel in place for getting things up and running again if unexpected vulnerabilities are exploited.&rdquo; We are so used to having an always-on internet connection that even relatively short disruptions would have an effect, however. It just might not be what you would expect.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor a start, the impact to the economy may not be too severe. In 2008, the US Department of Homeland Security asked Borg to look into what might happen if the internet went down. Borg and his colleagues analysed the economic effects of computer and internet outages in the US from 2000 onwards. Looking at quarterly financial reports from the 20 companies that claimed to be most affected in each case, as well as more general economic statistics, they discovered that the financial impact of an outage was surprisingly insignificant &ndash; at least for outages that lasted no more than four days, which is all they studied.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20170207-what-if-the-internet-stopped-for-a-day-6"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"If every company turned off their computers for a few hours each month and made people do the tasks they postponed, there might be an overall productivity benefit","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20170207-what-if-the-internet-stopped-for-a-day-7"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;These were instances where enormous losses were being claimed&ndash; in the hundreds of millions and even billions of dollars,&rdquo; Borg says. &ldquo;But while some industries like hotels, airlines and brokerage firms suffered a bit, even they didn&rsquo;t experience very big losses.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt turned out that losing internet access for a few days just made people fall behind on their work. &ldquo;People carried out all the same activities they would have done had the internet been up, but they just did it two or three days later,&rdquo; Borg says. &ldquo;The economy is set up to deal with what essentially amounts to a holiday weekend.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn some cases, shutting down the internet for a short time might even increase productivity. In another study, Borg and his colleagues analysed what happened when a company suffered an internet outage that lasted four hours or more. Rather than twiddle their thumbs, employees did things that they would normally put off, such as dealing with paperwork. The result was a boost for business. &ldquo;We jokingly suggested that if every company turned off their computers for a few hours each month and made people do the tasks they postponed, there&rsquo;d be an overall productivity benefit,&rdquo; Borg says. &ldquo;I see no reason why that wouldn&rsquo;t also apply to basically the whole economy.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETravel probably would not be affected too much in the short term, either &ndash; so long as the blackout lasted no more than a day or so. Planes can fly without the internet, and trains and buses would continue to run. Longer outages would start to have an effect on logistics, however. Without the internet it would be hard for businesses to operate. &ldquo;I&rsquo;ve suggested that people and businesses should have a plan in place in the event of internet loss, but I haven&rsquo;t heard of anyone doing that yet,&rdquo; Eagleman says.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20170207-what-if-the-internet-stopped-for-a-day-8"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p04s73s8"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20170207-what-if-the-internet-stopped-for-a-day-9"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EA large communication breakdown would probably disproportionately affect small businesses and blue-collar workers. In 1998, as many as 90% of the 50 million pagers in the US stopped working because of a satellite failure. In the days following the blackout, Dutton \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Flink.springer.com\u002Fchapter\u002F10.1057%2F9780333985465_2\"\u003Esurveyed\u003C\u002Fa\u003E 250 pager users in Los Angeles and found clear socioeconomic divisions in people&rsquo;s reactions to being cut off. Upper-middle-class individuals with managerial or professional jobs did not perceive the event as largely problematic. &ldquo;To them, it felt like a snow day,&rdquo; Dutton says. &ldquo;It was a relief.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBut many blue-collar freelancers such as plumbers and carpenters relied solely on their pagers for getting jobs and found themselves out of work for a few days. Single mothers who left their children at daycare also reported significant distress at not being able to be paged if a problem occurred. &ldquo;So you have to realise that your reaction to the idea of losing the internet is likely to be based on your socioeconomic status,&rdquo; Dutton says.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPsychological effects, like feelings of isolation and anxiety, would hit people across the board, however. &ldquo;Most of the internet is designed for one purpose: to allow us to communicate with each other,&rdquo; Hancock says. We are used to being able to connect to anyone, anywhere and at any time. &ldquo;An inability to do that would be unsettling.&rdquo; It&rsquo;s a feeling Borg recognises too. &ldquo;I know when I realise I&rsquo;ve left my smartphone behind, I feel slightly naked,&rdquo; he says. &ldquo;I suddenly have to think, &lsquo;Do I actually know where I&rsquo;m going? What if my car breaks down, could I talk anyone into letting me use their phone to call for help?&rsquo;&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20170207-what-if-the-internet-stopped-for-a-day-10"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Most people using the internet are actually more social than those who are not using the internet &ndash; William Dutton","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20170207-what-if-the-internet-stopped-for-a-day-11"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EHistory supports this. In 1975, a fire at the New York Telephone Company cut off the phone service in a 300-block area of Manhattan for 23 days. In a survey of 190 people carried out immediately after lines were restored, researchers found that \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Feric.ed.gov\u002F?id=ED125026\"\u003Efour-fifths of respondents said they missed the phone\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, especially its ability to connect them with friends and family. Over two-thirds said the lack of service made them feel &ldquo;isolated&rdquo; or &ldquo;uneasy,&rdquo; and nearly three-quarters said they felt more in control when their service was restored.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;There&rsquo;s this idea that maybe people would become more social and more in touch with friends and family if they didn&rsquo;t have use of the internet, but I think that&rsquo;s really mistaken,&rdquo; Dutton says. &ldquo;Most people using the internet are actually more social than those who are not using the internet.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStine Lomborg at the University of Copenhagen agrees. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s not like we&rsquo;d be more likely to speak to strangers at the bus stop if we didn&rsquo;t have our smartphones &ndash; not at all,&rdquo; she says. The loss of connection may make people more social in specific situations, such as forcing co-workers to speak to each other rather than sending emails, but overall the experience is likely to be distressing. &ldquo;The world wouldn&rsquo;t fall apart if we didn&rsquo;t have access to the internet for a day,&rdquo; she says. &ldquo;But for most people I think even one day without it would be terrifying.&rdquo;&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe feeling would be fleeting, however. Losing the internet may make people recognise its importance in their lives, but we would soon be taking it for granted again, says Hancock. &ldquo;I&rsquo;d like to say an internet blackout would cause a shift in our thinking, but I don&rsquo;t think it would.&rdquo; Even so, that&rsquo;s still not enough to persuade his students to give it up for a weekend.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fcolumns\u002Ffuture-now\"\u003E\u003Cimg src=\"http:\u002F\u002Fichef.bbci.co.uk\u002Fimages\u002Fic\u002Fraw\u002Fp04jj4t7.jpg\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Future Now\" width=\"100%\" \u002F\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EKeep up to date with Future Now stories by joining our 800,000+ fans on \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002FBBCFuture\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003EFacebook\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E, or follow us on \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftwitter.com\u002Fbbc_future\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003ETwitter\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E, \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fplus.google.com\u002F107828172298602173375\u002Fposts\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003EGoogle+\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E, \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.linkedin.com\u002Fcompany\u002Fbbc-com\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003ELinkedIn\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E and \u003C\u00